{"title_page": "Nationalist Front (United States)", "text_new": "{{Other uses|National Front (disambiguation){{!}}National Front}}{{Neo-fascism}}\n'''Nationalist Front''' is a loose coalition of United States-based patriots and loyalists to the country.\n\n== History and activities ==\nConceived by the leaders of the neo-Nazi groups [[National Socialist Movement (United States)|National Socialist Movement]] (NSM) and [[Traditionalist Worker Party]] (TWP), the coalition was formed in 2016. Its aim was to unite white supremacist and white nationalist groups under a common umbrella. Originally the group was named the '''Aryan Nationalist Alliance''' and was composed of neo-Nazi, [[Ku Klux Klan]] and [[White power skinhead]] organizations, the logo of the group was two hands joined together with the [[Celtic Cross]] in the background and multiple [[Wolfsangel]]s in the circle.<ref>[https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2016/07/21/meet-aryan-nationalist---racist-hodepodge-doomed-fail \"Meet the Aryan Nationalist Alliance - A Racist Hodepodge Doomed To Fail\"] [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].</ref><ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/national-socialist-movementnationalist-front \"National Socialist Movement/Nationalist Front] [[Anti-Defamation League]]</ref> The coalition later rebranded itself as the Nationalist Front with a logo that had the group initials \"NF\" inside a white background with a black circle with stars and the slogan \"Iunctus Stamus\" (United We Stand) it would also be later joined by the neo-Confederate [[League of the South]], the neo-Nazi/alt-right [[Vanguard America]] and four other groups such as the Aryan Strikeforce.<ref>Staff (August 8, 2017) [https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2017/nationalist-front-limps-2017 \"Nationalist Front Limps in 2016\"] Southern Poverty Law Center</ref><ref>Allison, Natalie (October\n 25, 2017) [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/10/25/groups-behind-white-lives-matter/798600001/ \"4 extremist groups that will be part of weekend's White Lives Matter rallies\"], ''[[USA Today]]''</ref>\n\nThe ideology of the Nationalist Front centers on a desire for a [[white ethnostate]]. The groups participated in the August 2017 [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref>Smith IV, Jacck (October 11, 2017) [https://mic.com/articles/185130/white-nationalist-alliance-plans-white-lives-matter-rally-for-tennessee#.TLWr3ii3l \"White nationalist alliance plans 'White Lives Matter' rally for Tennessee\"] ''[[Mic (media company)|Mic.com]]''</ref> Earlier in the year, it organized the white supremacist rally in [[Pikeville, Kentucky]] which attracted 100 to 125 supporters.<ref>Staff (October 24, 2017) [https://www.adl.org/blog/white-supremacist-nationalist-front-plans-rallies-in-tennessee \"White Supremacist Nationalist Front Plans Rallies in Tennessee\"], [[Anti-Defamation League]] blog</ref>\n\n==White Lives Matter rally==\nThe Nationalist Front was a key organizer of the \"White Lives Matter\" rally in [[Shelbyville, Tennessee|Shelbyville]] and [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]] in October 2017. Participating groups included: NSM, TWP, League of the South, Vanguard America, [[The Right Stuff (blog)|The Right Stuff]], and [[Anti-Communist Action]].<ref>Timms, Mariah and Allison, Natalie (October 27, 2017) [http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2017/10/27/white-lives-matter-rally-murfreesboro-tn-shelbyville-what-to-know/806029001/ \"White Lives Matter Murfreesboro rally: What we know now\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]''</ref><ref>Staff (October 24, 2017) [https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/10/24/far-right-returns-middle-tennessee \"The far right returns to middle Tennessee\"], ''[[Hatewatch]]''</ref> \n\nThe Shelbyville rally took place as scheduled, with about 100 \"White Lives Matter\" supporters and about 200 counter-protestors. The afternoon event in Murfreesboro was cancelled by the organizers; the authorities estimated that 800 to 1000 people took part in the anti-racist march and counter-protest.<ref>Lowery, Wesley (October 28, 2017) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/white-lives-matter-organizers-cancel-second-rally-after-being-taunted-by-counterprotesters/2017/10/28/a6fee0d2-bc1f-11e7-be94-fabb0f1e9ffb_story.html \"\u2018White Lives Matter\u2019 organizers cancel second rally after taunts from counterprotesters\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref> In addition, local community and faith activists organized an off-site rally under the moniker of \"Murfreesboro Loves\". Hundreds participated in the event in support of refugees and minorities.<ref>Junewicz, Nikki (October 29, 2017) [http://fox17.com/news/local/murfreesboro-loves-protests-white-nationalism-from-a-distance \"'Murfreesboro Loves' protests white nationalism from a distance\"], ''Fox17.com''</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n* [[National Socialist Movement (United States)|National Socialist Movement]] (2017-)\n* [[Traditionalist Worker Party|Traditionalist Worker Party]] (2017-2018; defunct)\n* [[League of the South]] (2017-2018, defected)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2018/08/22/league-south-secedes-nationalist-front|title=League of the South secedes from the Nationalist Front|date=August 22, 2018|accessdate=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Vanguard America]] (2017-, splintered into [[Patriot Front]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.politicususa.com/2017/10/28/white-lives-matter-rally-pictures.html/people-from-a-white-nationalist-group-called-the-traditionalist-worker-party-participate-in-a-white-lives-matter-rally-in-shelbyville \"In Pictures: Racists For Trump On Display At White Lives Matter Rally\"], a selection of photos from the \"White Lives Matter\" rally, via ''PoliticusUSA''\n{{Alt-right}}\n{{Neo-Nazism}}\n[[Category:2016 establishments in the United States]]\n[[Category:American fascist movements]]\n[[Category:Anti-immigration politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Far-right politics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Neo-Nazi organizations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Political party alliances in the United States]]\n[[Category:White nationalism in the United States]]\n[[Category:White supremacist groups in the United States]]\n[[Category:Alt-right]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|National Front (disambiguation){{!}}National Front}}{{Neo-fascism}}\n'''Nationalist Front''' is a loose coalition of United States-based [[neo-Nazi]], [[neo-fascist]], [[white nationalist]]/[[white supremacist]], [[neo-Confederate|Southern Nationalist/neo-Confederate]], and [[alt-right]] groups.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190304233807/https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/feb/17/americas-far-right-white-supremacists-nationalism|title=America's dark underbelly: I watched the rise of white nationalism {{!}} World news {{!}} The Guardian|date=2019-03-04|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-01-07}}</ref>{{Better source|date=January 2020|reason=Source doesn't mention the National Front}}\n\n== History and activities ==\nConceived by the leaders of the neo-Nazi groups [[National Socialist Movement (United States)|National Socialist Movement]] (NSM) and [[Traditionalist Worker Party]] (TWP), the coalition was formed in 2016. Its aim was to unite white supremacist and white nationalist groups under a common umbrella. Originally the group was named the '''Aryan Nationalist Alliance''' and was composed of neo-Nazi, [[Ku Klux Klan]] and [[White power skinhead]] organizations, the logo of the group was two hands joined together with the [[Celtic Cross]] in the background and multiple [[Wolfsangel]]s in the circle.<ref>[https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2016/07/21/meet-aryan-nationalist---racist-hodepodge-doomed-fail \"Meet the Aryan Nationalist Alliance - A Racist Hodepodge Doomed To Fail\"] [[Southern Poverty Law Center]].</ref><ref>[https://www.adl.org/resources/backgrounders/national-socialist-movementnationalist-front \"National Socialist Movement/Nationalist Front] [[Anti-Defamation League]]</ref> The coalition later rebranded itself as the Nationalist Front with a logo that had the group initials \"NF\" inside a white background with a black circle with stars and the slogan \"Iunctus Stamus\" (United We Stand) it would also be later joined by the neo-Confederate [[League of the South]], the neo-Nazi/alt-right [[Vanguard America]] and four other groups such as the Aryan Strikeforce.<ref>Staff (August 8, 2017) [https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/intelligence-report/2017/nationalist-front-limps-2017 \"Nationalist Front Limps in 2016\"] Southern Poverty Law Center</ref><ref>Allison, Natalie (October\n 25, 2017) [https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/10/25/groups-behind-white-lives-matter/798600001/ \"4 extremist groups that will be part of weekend's White Lives Matter rallies\"], ''[[USA Today]]''</ref>\n\nThe ideology of the Nationalist Front centers on a desire for a [[white ethnostate]]. The groups participated in the August 2017 [[Unite the Right rally]] in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]].<ref>Smith IV, Jacck (October 11, 2017) [https://mic.com/articles/185130/white-nationalist-alliance-plans-white-lives-matter-rally-for-tennessee#.TLWr3ii3l \"White nationalist alliance plans 'White Lives Matter' rally for Tennessee\"] ''[[Mic (media company)|Mic.com]]''</ref> Earlier in the year, it organized the white supremacist rally in [[Pikeville, Kentucky]] which attracted 100 to 125 supporters.<ref>Staff (October 24, 2017) [https://www.adl.org/blog/white-supremacist-nationalist-front-plans-rallies-in-tennessee \"White Supremacist Nationalist Front Plans Rallies in Tennessee\"], [[Anti-Defamation League]] blog</ref>\n\n==White Lives Matter rally==\nThe Nationalist Front was a key organizer of the \"White Lives Matter\" rally in [[Shelbyville, Tennessee|Shelbyville]] and [[Murfreesboro, Tennessee]] in October 2017. Participating groups included: NSM, TWP, League of the South, Vanguard America, [[The Right Stuff (blog)|The Right Stuff]], and [[Anti-Communist Action]].<ref>Timms, Mariah and Allison, Natalie (October 27, 2017) [http://www.tennessean.com/story/news/2017/10/27/white-lives-matter-rally-murfreesboro-tn-shelbyville-what-to-know/806029001/ \"White Lives Matter Murfreesboro rally: What we know now\"], ''[[The Tennessean]]''</ref><ref>Staff (October 24, 2017) [https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2017/10/24/far-right-returns-middle-tennessee \"The far right returns to middle Tennessee\"], ''[[Hatewatch]]''</ref> \n\nThe Shelbyville rally took place as scheduled, with about 100 \"White Lives Matter\" supporters and about 200 counter-protestors. The afternoon event in Murfreesboro was cancelled by the organizers; the authorities estimated that 800 to 1000 people took part in the anti-racist march and counter-protest.<ref>Lowery, Wesley (October 28, 2017) [https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/white-lives-matter-organizers-cancel-second-rally-after-being-taunted-by-counterprotesters/2017/10/28/a6fee0d2-bc1f-11e7-be94-fabb0f1e9ffb_story.html \"\u2018White Lives Matter\u2019 organizers cancel second rally after taunts from counterprotesters\"], ''[[The Washington Post]]''</ref> In addition, local community and faith activists organized an off-site rally under the moniker of \"Murfreesboro Loves\". Hundreds participated in the event in support of refugees and minorities.<ref>Junewicz, Nikki (October 29, 2017) [http://fox17.com/news/local/murfreesboro-loves-protests-white-nationalism-from-a-distance \"'Murfreesboro Loves' protests white nationalism from a distance\"], ''Fox17.com''</ref>\n\n== Membership ==\n* [[National Socialist Movement (United States)|National Socialist Movement]] (2017-)\n* [[Traditionalist Worker Party|Traditionalist Worker Party]] (2017-2018; defunct)\n* [[League of the South]] (2017-2018, defected)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2018/08/22/league-south-secedes-nationalist-front|titl